## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**10 tests. 0 real verifications.** This is a textbook **coverage-touching** suite — every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called exactly once, in declaration order, with no meaningful assertions. Code-coverage tools report ~95% line coverage, but these tests would still pass if every method returned garbage, corrupted data, or silently did nothing.

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| 🔴 Critical | 6 |
| 🟠 High | 1 |
| 🟡 Medium | 2 |

---

### 🔴 Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage-touching pattern (systemic — entire class)

The suite methodically walks the entire `ProductCatalog` surface area. 6 of 10 tests have **zero assertions** and 3 more use only `Assert.IsNotNull`, which proves nothing about correctness.

#### 2. No assertions — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17)

Calls `AddProduct` but never verifies the product was actually stored.

```csharp
// FIX:
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_StoresProduct()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);
    Assert.AreEqual(product, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
}
```

#### 3. No assertions — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32)

Calls `UpdatePrice` but never checks the price actually changed.

```csharp
// FIX:
[TestMethod]
public void UpdatePrice_ChangesPriceOfExistingProduct()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
    Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001")!.Price);
}
```

#### 4. No assertions — `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 39)

Calls `RemoveProduct` but never verifies the product is gone. A no-op `Delete` would pass.

```csharp
// FIX:
[TestMethod]
public void RemoveProduct_ProductNoLongerRetrievable()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
}
```

#### 5. No assertions — `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63)

Discards the return value entirely. Doesn't even call `Assert.IsNotNull`.

```csharp
// FIX:
[TestMethod]
public void GetProductCount_ReturnsNumberOfStoredProducts()
{
    Assert.AreEqual(0, _catalog.GetProductCount());
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    Assert.AreEqual(1, _catalog.GetProductCount());
